## 4. Domain Models

Use `sealed record` for all DTOs. Use `required` on every mandatory property. Never use nullable properties as a workaround for missing required values.

```csharp
// Models/Create{{ model.names.dot_net_class_name }}Request.cs
public sealed record Create{{ model.names.dot_net_class_name }}Request
{
    [Required]
    [StringLength(100, MinimumLength = 1)]
    public required string Reference { get; init; }

    [Required]
    [StringLength(200)]
    public required string SubmittedBy { get; init; }

    public required DateTimeOffset SubmittedAt { get; init; }
}

// Models/{{ model.names.dot_net_class_name }}Response.cs  — replace generated placeholder
public sealed record {{ model.names.dot_net_class_name }}Response
{
    public required string Id { get; init; }
    public required string Reference { get; init; }
    public required string Status { get; init; }
    public required DateTimeOffset CreatedAt { get; init; }
    public required DateTimeOffset UpdatedAt { get; init; }
}
```

### Domain exceptions

Create specific exceptions so the controller maps them cleanly:

```csharp
// Exceptions/YourDomainNotFoundException.cs
public sealed class YourDomainNotFoundException : Exception
{
    public string RecordId { get; }

    public YourDomainNotFoundException(string id)
        : base($"Record '{id}' was not found.")
    {
        RecordId = id;
    }
}

// Exceptions/YourDomainDuplicateException.cs
public sealed class YourDomainDuplicateException : Exception
{
    public string Reference { get; }

    public YourDomainDuplicateException(string reference)
        : base($"A record with reference '{reference}' already exists.")
    {
        Reference = reference;
    }
}
```

