## 10. Adding a New Feature — Step-by-Step

Follow this exact order every time:

```
1. Define domain exceptions (if new failure modes)
   └── Exceptions/YourDomainXxxException.cs

2. Add request/response records
   └── Models/XxxRequest.cs, Models/XxxResponse.cs

3. Extend the service interface
   └── Services/IService.cs

4. Update entity and add migration (if schema changes)
   └── Data/YourDomainEntity.cs
   └── dotnet ef migrations add <Name>

5. Implement repository method
   └── Data/YourDomainRepository.cs

6. Implement service method
   └── Services/{{ model.names.dot_net_class_name }}Impl.cs
   └── Add logging + tracing + metrics

7. Add controller endpoint
   └── Controllers/Controller.cs
   └── Route, ProducesResponseType, error mapping

8. Write tests
   └── Tests/Services/ → unit tests
   └── Tests/Controllers/ → integration tests

9. Verify coverage
   └── dotnet test --collect:"XPlat Code Coverage"
```

---

## 11. What NOT To Do

| Don't | Do instead |
|---|---|
| Use AutoMapper or Mapster | Write explicit mapping methods (see `anti-patterns-and-reflection.md`) |
| Put business logic in controllers | Move it to `{{ model.names.dot_net_class_name }}` service |
| Call EF Core directly from controllers | Go through the repository interface |
| Call Genesis providers from controllers | Go through the service |
| Use `.Result` or `.Wait()` | `await` all async calls |
| Log PII (name, email, phone) | Log IDs and operation names only |
| Add NuGet packages without approval | Raise a ticket per `DEPENDENCY_MANAGEMENT.md` |
| Modify `Program.cs` | Raise a Pervaxis platform ticket |
| Skip tests | 90% coverage is a CI gate — the pipeline blocks the PR |

